President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 15th as White Cane Safety Day, recognizing the contributions of Americans who are blind or have low vision. The white cane serves as a symbol of dignity, freedom, and independence for individuals with visual impairments. The proclamation emphasizes the progress made in education for students with disabilities and the need to ensure accessibility to technology and assistive tools. The administration is committed to increasing information access and expanding career options for people with disabilities. The proclamation also highlights the importance of Braille literacy and the celebration of the 20th anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act. The President calls upon public officials, business and community leaders, educators, librarians, and Americans to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies and programs.